2016: Curating Your Teaching Portfolio: Selection and Reflection (Online) at Online

You’ve taught courses
column4: you’ve written (or thought about) your teaching philosophy
column6: but your online teaching portfolio is still missing something important: teaching material. An e-portfolio can help define your professional identity online
column7: but it can be challenging to select and arrange the stuff of a career to present a thoughtful and coherent whole. What do you need to include? What can you afford to leave out? How much explanation does it all require? Online attention spans are notoriously short
column8: so an effective teaching portfolio provides carefully-selected artifacts of your teaching practice that complement the rest of your portfolio documents and invite visitors to learn about your work.

column1: This workshop offers you the opportunity to curate your teaching portfolio while exchanging feedback with other faculty members. Drawing on both teaching portfolio guides and the evolving pedagogy that helps students create effective portfolios at DePaul and many other universities
column2: this workshop will guide you through the processes of selection and reflection to create a holistic picture of you as a teacher. After a review of some best practices
column3: we’ll discuss how to align the various audiences and purposes your portfolio is intended for and the teaching material you have to work with. We’ll examine sample portfolios
column4: go through a structured analysis of our own portfolio material
column5: and work together to plan the next iteration of our online professional identities.

column1: Identify appropriate and engaging artifacts that reflect their teaching practice.
Plan a revision of their teaching portfolios that integrate their artifacts into a coherent whole
column2: supporting the claims of reflections and the teaching philosophy.

column1: Introduce teaching artifacts with reflective comments that take multiple audiences into account.
Format: This workshop is fully online and asynchronous
column2: meaning that there are no face-to-face meetings. Participants must have reliable access to the Internet during the week of January 19-24
column3: and should count on committing to approximately three hours in total to the workshop activities. After the end date
column4: you will retain access to the materials and activities on the workshop's D2L site. Enrollment for this workshop is capped at 25 individuals.

column3: and should have sample teaching materials on hand that they might choose to include in a teaching portfolio. This workshop will be useful to individuals considering making a digital teaching portfolio
column4: those who are already in the process of creating their portfolio

2016: Giving Back in Ghana: Thomas Awiapo's Story of Survival to Success at Library - Richardson Library Lincoln Park Campus

~ RSVP by Jan. 22 to ksulli47@depaul.edu
a global solidarity coordinator for Catholic Relief Services (CRS) in Ghana
column3: shares his story of survival & success with us at this casual
column4: brown bag/BYO lunch event (drinks & dessert provided).

column1: Growing up in a small African village in Ghana
column2: Thomas was orphaned before the age of 10 and left on his own to struggle for survival. He was the second of four brothers; his youngest two brothers died of malnutrition and lack of care.

column1: His search for food led him to an elementary school
column2: where he was fed a small meal every day. He survived
column4: and eventually won scholarships to attend college. He later earned a master’s degree from California State University.

column2: he works for CRS training community leaders throughout Ghana
column3: where he lives with his wife and four children. His story of initiative and his joyful presence has brought inspiration to thousands of people in the U.S.

column3: and the Soft Prejudice of Liberalism"

column4: and government have increasingly raised their voices about what they see as an Islamic threat. To deflect accusations of prejudice and Western triumphalism
column5: they couch their discourses in language that targets Islam's foreign "ism" affix: Islamism. This narrative is of immense appeal to neoconservatives and progressives alike. But it's not without consequences. In a provocative evening discussion at DePaul University's Cortelyou Commons
column6: author and scholar Nathan Lean will examine the ways in which Islamophobia has become a byproduct of Western liberalism
column7: and entrenched itself among a group of people that have long claimed to champion multiculturalism and religious freedom.

2016: Jessica Chiarella reading at Library - Richardson Library Lincoln Park Campus

Please join the Department of English in celebrating the release of recent DePaul MAWP graduate Jessica Chiarella's first novel

column1: AND AGAIN is the story of four terminally-ill patients who are given new
column2: cloned bodies as part of a pilot program called SUBlife. While the “SUBs” are exact replicas of the patients’ former bodies
column4: spared the onslaught of environmental damage that accompanies a normal life. Their vision is perfect. Old injuries disappear. Food tastes different. Scars
column6: and even the muscle memory they have always taken for granted is now gone. Their lives are saved
column7: but their physical identities have been wiped away.

column1: The novel follows these characters as they reenter their lives and find that they have been both restored
column5: discovers she can no longer paint. David
column7: attempts to hide his transformation from the public even as he continues to grapple with his old habits. Connie
column8: an actress whose bombshell looks are restored after a protracted illness
column9: attempts to navigate an industry obsessed with physical beauty. And Linda
column10: who spent eight years paralyzed after an auto accident
column11: finds she can no longer connect with the family she once loved. Throughout the following year
column12: their return to health proves fraught with unbelievable rewards

column1: "And Again is a moving and beautifully crafted novel about the frailty of identity
column3: and the enduring power of love. A fantastic debut."-Laila Lalami
column5: Pulitzer Prize finalist and longlisted for the Man Booker Prize

column2: Jessica Chiarella is a graduate of DePaul's MAWP program and is currently a student in the University of California
column3: Riverside's MFA in Creative Writing program.

2016: Dimensions of Communication at DePaul Center (DPC)

Explore the discipline of communication through faculty and student presentations ‘powered’ by the global phenomenon PechaKucha20x20 — 20 images

the PechaKucha (say pe-chahk’-cha) presentation format was created in 2003 by a group of Tokyo architectural designers as a concise way to showcase their work to the public. These first meetings included networking and socializing
column3: and soon the PechaKucha Night (PKN) was born. Nearly twelve years and 700 cities later
column4: PKNs are a worldwide phenomenon where artists
column8: and creatives come together and present their work in a social environment. To learn more about PechaKucha 20x20

column1: Shana’s pechakucha is about understanding her identity as an Iranian woman while breaking the stereotype of Middle Eastern women that is per- ceived in the West. She celebrates political and social change through the voices of Iranian women by emphasizing the strength in their resistance. Her presentation will begin with a personal poem followed by analysis and a brief description of Iran’s political history.
Climate Activists Took to Social Media for Paris Climate Talks but Who are They Reaching? And

column2: representatives of 195 nations meeting in Paris for the Conference of the Parties (COP21) set an ambitious goal to reach net zero greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by the mid-century. During the talks climate activists took to social media to get out their message on climate justice
column3: but did they reach people on social media who are not already supporters of action on climate change? Hopke’s analysis of social media during the climate summit explores interaction between climate activists and the industry most closely associated with carbon emissions: oil and gas. She also discusses the implications for future climate action and our collective ability to live up to the goals set at COP21.

column1: Screams from the Basement: DIY Punk Shows in the USA
Makagon’s pechakucha explores the development of a DIY punk touring network in the US
column2: focusing on the shift from regional shows featuring local bands to more organized national touring options. More specifically
column3: the transformation of the house as a private space to a pseudo-public show space for local punks to do DIY is discussed.

column1: How Young Uninsured Americans Respond to Obamacare News Coverage: Why Journalists’ Choice of Examples Matter

Martin and Myrick’s study is the first large-scale interdisciplinary merger of political communication and health communication theory in a critical real-world empirical context. They explore how journalists’ choices in reporting online news affects how people think
column2: feel and act regarding their own health – and subsequently
column3: how those effects hold important consequences for public health. Their online experiment (N=1
column4: 056) found that the positivity or negativity of the case studies
column6: that journalists choose to include have direct effects on young uninsured Americans. The results highlight the important role journalists play in communicating the realities of complicated legislation and public health issues.

column1: When Lives Are on the Line: Communicating in High-Reliability Organizations
Murphy’s pechakucha will focus on her work with high-stakes communication within organizations such as hospital emergency rooms.

column2: Heart Korean: Non-Korean Identities in U.S. Korean Meetup Groups

column1: Meetup.com is a social networking site that boasts nearly 14
column2: 000 local interest-based groups worldwide including more than 50 Korean language and culture Meetup groups in the United States. Ter Molen’s ethnographic study recorded the lived experiences of non-Korean members of these groups to explore why Korean culture resonates with them to the extent that they appropriate Korean cultural symbols and seek out other Koreanophiles with whom they create new meanings. Most importantly
column3: her study seeks to understand how their participation in Korean cultural activities shapes their own identities.

column1: Healing Water: A Narrative for My Dear Friend H20
Schultz has been a fish her whole life; the mental and physical healing power of water is something to which only swimmers can attest. Finding peace in the water always came easy to Schultz
column2: but after a scary knee injury she struggled for years on her way back upstream. Until she dove back in.

column4:

Joshua Hawkins Nannestad, Assistant Professor of Choral Music Education, Southeastern Oklahoma State University

Daniel A. Dombrowski, Professor of Philosophy, Seattle University

Mark Potosnak, Associate Professor of Environmental Science and Studies, DePaul University

Robert Beatty, Director of Music, Saint vincent de Paul Parish with The Saint Vincent de Paul Chamber Chorale and musicians from the DePaul community

Wine and Cheese Reception* @ 8:30 PM - 9:00 PM

column1: OVERVIEW: Bookended by the falling of the Berlin Wall and the Twin Towers
column2: the 1990s may appear to have been a peaceful and prosperous decade for America. But closer inspection reveals a fraught period for the nation?s politics
column3: according to Gil Troy. Domestically this was an era of rising extremism and violence
column4: including the Oklahoma City bombing and Waco Siege. Further afield
column5: America wrestled with whether to intervene to halt genocides in Africa and the Balkans. Meanwhile
column6: the clash of a liberal president and a resurgent conservative movement fostered an increasingly partisan political climate. At the center of the storm was the Baby Boomer president
column10: and indiscretions would dominate the decade. What is the political legacy of the turbulent 90s
column11: and how might it impact the prospects for another Clinton presidency?

column1: Gil Troy?s new Book The Age of Clinton: America in the 1990s will be available for sale and signing after the program from The Book Cellar.

column1: OVERVIEW: Europe is still facing a complex environment. The economic recovery is slowing
column2: despite an ongoing European Central Bank stimulus package and low energy prices?and the euro zone is still a monetary but not a fiscal union. The internal dynamics of the European Union are also strained by increased security concerns
column6: the integration of the continent?s economies and societies seems to have halted?as exemplified by the new border fences being constructed by various countries. Will Europe emerge stronger or weaker from these trials? Please join The Chicago Council and Luigi Zingales for a discussion on the future of Europe.

column1: SPEAKER: Luigi Zingales is the Robert C. McCormack Professor of Entrepreneurship and Finance
column2: and Charles M. Harper Faculty Fellow at the University of Chicago Booth School of Business
column3: where he has worked since 1992. In July 2015 he also became the director of the Stigler Center at the University of Chicago
column4: which promotes and diffuses research on regulatory capture and the various distortions that special interest groups impose on capitalism. Zingales also serves as a fellow at the National Bureau of Economic Research
column5: the Center for Economic Policy Research
column7: as well as on the Committee on Capital Markets Regulation. In 2014
column8: he was the President of the American Finance Association. From 2005 to 2006
column9: he served as the Taussig Research Professor at Harvard University. Zingales received the 2003 Bernacer Prize
column10: awarded to European economists under the age of forty who have made outstanding contributions in macroeconomics and finance
column11: and the 2002 NASDAQ award for best paper on capital formation. He earned his BA from Universita Bocconi in Italy and his PhD from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.

2016: Semiotics and the Study of Jewish Culture in Late Antiquity at Cortelyou Commons

Host: Alexei Sivertsev

column1: Description: Scholars have increasingly turned to the category of semiotics to construct their narratives of late antiquity. In the words of Thomas Sizgorich
column5: and associations constituted a semiotic brew in late antiquity that united diverse communities otherwise separated by language
column7: and dogma across a geographical expanse stretching from Ireland to Yemen. This panel sets out to discuss the implications of a semiotic study of late antiquity for our interpretation of Jewish art and literature produced between the third and the eighth centuries of the Common Era.

column1: Mira Balberg is assistant professor of Religious Studies at Northwestern University. She is the author of Purity
column3: and Self in Early Rabbinic Literature (University of California Press
column4: 2014) and of Gateway to Rabbinic Literature (פתח לספרות חז"ל) (The Open University of Israel Press
column5: 2013). Other topics on which she has published include questions of personhood in rabbinic literature
column6: the human body and its changing cultural meanings in ancient Jewish texts
column7: and the production of knowledge in late antiquity. She is currently working on a book exploring the transformation of sacrifice in early rabbinic literature. ​

column1: Ra‘anan Boustan is an Associate Professor in the Department of History at the University of California
column2: Los Angeles. His research and teaching explore the dynamic intersections between Judaism and other Mediterranean religious traditions. He is the author of From Martyr to Mystic: Rabbinic Martyrology and the Making of Merkavah Mysticism (2005)
column3: has published widely in leading journals such as Harvard Theological Review
column8: most recently a special issue of the journal Archiv für Religionsgeschichte on “Authoritative Traditions and Ritual Power in the Ancient World” (2015).

2016: Semiotics and the Study of Jewish Culture in Late Antiquity at Cortelyou Commons

Host: Alexei Sivertsev

column1: Description: Scholars have increasingly turned to the category of semiotics to construct their narratives of late antiquity. In the words of Thomas Sizgorich
column5: and associations constituted a semiotic brew in late antiquity that united diverse communities otherwise separated by language
column7: and dogma across a geographical expanse stretching from Ireland to Yemen. This panel sets out to discuss the implications of a semiotic study of late antiquity for our interpretation of Jewish art and literature produced between the third and the eighth centuries of the Common Era.

column1: Mira Balberg is assistant professor of Religious Studies at Northwestern University. She is the author of Purity
column3: and Self in Early Rabbinic Literature (University of California Press
column4: 2014) and of Gateway to Rabbinic Literature (פתח לספרות חז"ל) (The Open University of Israel Press
column5: 2013). Other topics on which she has published include questions of personhood in rabbinic literature
column6: the human body and its changing cultural meanings in ancient Jewish texts
column7: and the production of knowledge in late antiquity. She is currently working on a book exploring the transformation of sacrifice in early rabbinic literature. ​

column1: Ra‘anan Boustan is an Associate Professor in the Department of History at the University of California
column2: Los Angeles. His research and teaching explore the dynamic intersections between Judaism and other Mediterranean religious traditions. He is the author of From Martyr to Mystic: Rabbinic Martyrology and the Making of Merkavah Mysticism (2005)
column3: has published widely in leading journals such as Harvard Theological Review
column8: most recently a special issue of the journal Archiv für Religionsgeschichte on “Authoritative Traditions and Ritual Power in the Ancient World” (2015).

2016: DeAndreis-Rosati Memorial Archives (DRMA) Lecture at Library - Richardson Library Lincoln Park Campus

Lecturer: Thérèse Peeters

column1: Title: The role of trust in the Vincentian Missions in North Africa (1645-1689)

My research into the correspondence of seventeenth century Vincentian missionaries on the Barbary Coast (1645-1689) has revealed an aspect of the Catholic missions that has not yet been thoroughly considered: the role of trust in the success or failure of these missions. Being confronted with a hostile Muslim environment
column2: the dreadful situation of the slaves
column3: and with the greatest enemy of all
column5: the Vincentian Missionaries needed to be in a good relationship with Vincent de Paul
column7: and with the cardinals of  Propaganda Fide in Rome. As is apparent from the two case studies that I will present
column8: this initial trust was continuously reconsidered both by De Paul and Propaganda Fide. Historians have recently shown that early modern people consciously thought about whom to trust
column9: and that trust and trustworthiness are realities that can be studied historically. I argue that it can also be a valuable lens through which to reach a better understanding of early modern Catholic missions: the extensive correspondence between the founder of the Congregation of the Mission and his followers overseas
column10: is a rich treasure from which to learn about this poorly considered aspect of the missionary world of the seventeenth century.

column2: Thérèse Peeters completed her BA in Italian language and culture
column3: and her BA in history at Leiden University. During her master Medieval and early modern European history at the same university
column4: she specialized on missionary correspondence and the role of trust. She also collaborated at the project “Vincent de Paul
column6: and the Papacy: Documents from the Vatican Archives (1625-1670)
column7: ” a digital catalogue of archival sources and a digital edition of selected documents. She is currently working on her PhD project

Join us for our weekly trip to Ozanam Village/Matthew Manor on Saturday morning at 9:30am. We will meet outside of the Catholic Campus Ministries(CCM) office [Room 104] on the first floor of the LPC Student Center.
